  "prompt": "What is derivation Of E=mc^2?",
  "response": "The equation \\( E = mc^2 \\) is one of the most famous equations in physics, formulated by Albert Einstein as part of his theory of special relativity. It expresses the relationship between energy (\\( E \\)), mass (\\( m \\)), and the speed of light (\\( c \\)). Here's a simplified derivation of the equation:\n\n---\n\n### Basic Concepts:\n1. **Relativistic Energy**: In special relativity, the total energy of an object includes both its rest mass energy and its kinetic energy.\n2. **Rest Mass Energy**: Even when an object is at rest, it possesses energy due to its mass.\n3. **Speed of Light (\\( c \\))**: A constant (\\( c \\approx 3 \\times 10^8 \\, \\text{m/s} \\)) that plays a central role in relativity.\n\n---\n\n### Derivation:\n1. **Relativistic Momentum**:\n   The momentum (\\( p \\)) of an object moving at velocity (\\( v \\)) close to the speed of light is given by:\n   \\[\n   p = \\gamma m v\n   \\]\n   where \\( \\gamma \\) (the Lorentz factor) is:\n   \\[\n   \\gamma = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}}}\n   \\]\n\n2. **Energy-Momentum Relation**:\n   In special relativity, the total energy (\\( E \\)) and momentum (\\( p \\)) of an object are related by:\n   \\[\n   E^2 = (pc)^2 + (m c^2)^2\n   \\]\n   This is known as the energy-momentum relation.\n\n3. **Case of Resting Object**:\n   When the object is at rest (\\( v = 0 \\)), its momentum \\( p = 0 \\). Substituting \\( p = 0 \\) into the energy-momentum relation:\n   \\[\n   E^2 = (0)^2 + (m c^2)^2\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   E^2 = (m c^2)^2\n   \\]\n   Taking the square root of both sides:\n   \\[\n   E = m c^2\n   \\]\n\n---\n\n### Interpretation:\nThe equation \\( E = mc^2 \\) shows that even an object at rest has energy proportional to its mass. This energy is called the **rest mass energy**. It demonstrates the equivalence of mass and energy, a cornerstone of modern physics.\n\n---\n\n### Notes:\n- The full energy of a moving object includes both rest mass energy and kinetic energy.\n- The equation has profound implications for nuclear reactions, particle physics, and cosmology, where mass can be converted into energy and vice versa.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
